==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
According to Shuowen Jiezi, {{Han compound|糸|合|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p}} – "rich, abundant", perhaps with a reference to precious silk; today it also means "to give". The phonetic component means "to join, to unite", however it is likely unrelated to the original meaning.

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|s=给}}
{{zh-ref|Starostin}} reconstructs {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*qǝ̆p||to give; to supply}}, comparing it to {{cog|my|အပ်|tr=ap|t=to commit; to deliver; to hand over}}, {{cog|kac|ap||to hand over}}, {{cog|lep|ᰀᰤᰬᰱ|tr=kjep|t=to add to; to multiply}}, {{m|lep|ᰃᰤᰱ|tr=gjap|t=many}}.

In Mandarin, Jin and Xiang, pronunciations 1 and 2 are generally thought of as {{w|Literary and colloquial readings of Chinese characters|colloquial and literary readings}} respectively, from the same {{inh|zh|ltc|-}} etymon ({{zh-ref|Zhengzhang, 2002}}; {{zh-ref|Liu, 2021}}; among others). Pronunciation 2, the literary reading, is a regular reflex from {{inh|zh|ltc|-}}. However, since pronunciation 1 is highly irregular, others have proposed alternative etymologies for it:
* From the contraction of {{ltc-l|過與|to pass to|id=2,2}} ({{zh-ref|Ikeda, 1962}}; {{zh-ref|Hirayama, 2000, 2010}}; {{zh-ref|Wang, 2022}});
* From {{ltc-l|乞|to give}} ({{zh-ref|Zhang, 1989}}); and
* From {{ltc-l|饋|to gift}} ({{zh-ref|Shimura, 1995}}).

